-- ‘Kinky Boots,’ ‘Vanya,’ ‘Pippin’ Sales Rise Before Tonys
-- B y   P h i l i p   B o r o f f
-- 2013-05-20T23:00:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-20/-kinky-boots-vanya-pippin-sales-rise-before-tonys.html
“Matilda” got better reviews and is winning lots of awards, but “Kinky Boots” prevailed at the box office last week.  The high-kicking new Cyndi Lauper musical had its best week to date, selling $1.3 million of tickets in the seven days ending Sunday, according to the trade association the  Broadway League . Sales were up 1.5 percent.  “Matilda,” the bitter-sweet, tuneful comedy co-produced by the Royal Shakespeare Company and based on the Roald Dahl story, was named best musical at the Drama Desk Awards and by the  New York  Drama Critics’ Circle. It dipped 5 percent to $1.1 million.  Other winners in the penultimate week of the season: Christopher Durang’s Chekhov-inspired “Vanya and Sonia and Masha and Spike,” up 12 percent to $550,000; and the circuslike “Pippin,” up 1 percent to $869,000. They’re favorites at the Tonys for top new play and musical revival, respectively.  “Motown,” which wasn’t nominated for new musical, nevertheless climbed 6 percent to $1.2 million. The jukebox musical continues to draw crowds despite critical drubbing.  Sales Rise  Overall, Broadway sales rose 2 percent to $24.7 million. The season officially ends this weekend. CBS Television will broadcast the Tony Awards live from Radio City Music Hall on June 9.  Nominated for a best actress Tony for playing Texas Governor Ann Richards, television star Holland Taylor is performing “Ann” to houses near 40 percent of capacity. Sales rose 2 percent to $247,000. Despite critical acclaim for Cicely Tyson in Horton Foote’s “The Trip to Bountiful,” sales fell 17 percent, to $469,000.  “Spiderman: Turn off the Dark” was up 3 percent to $1 million, extending a multiweek run of barely covering its running expenses.  The Ambassador Theatre Group bought the long-term lease for its home, the Foxwoods Theatre, said an Ambassador spokesman, Rick Miramontez. The theater, at 1,930 seats, is Broadway’s biggest house.  The lease expires at year-end 2038, according to a filing from the previous lease holder,  Live Nation (LYV) , a concert producer. Ambassador has options to renew. The Foxwoods is one of seven theaters overseen by the nonprofit New 42nd St. and owned by  New York City .  Ambassador paid over $60 million for the lease, according to two people familiar with the acquisition who spoke on condition of anonymity.  Muse highlights include  Jeremy Gerard  on theater and  James S. Russell  on architecture.  To contact the reporter on this story: Philip Boroff in New York at  pboroff@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story: Manuela Hoelterhoff in New York at  mhoelterhoff@bloomberg.net . 